{
  "texts": [
    "The skein module A(N):= A(N × I) has the structure of a C * -algebra with multiplication of two elements [x] and [y] defined by gluing the bottom of [x] to the top of [y], and with *operation given by [x] * = [f (x)] where f: N ×I → N ×I: (θ, r) → (θ, 1-r).",
    "simple objects from Irr C to oriented edges of C. An internal labelling of C is an assignment l: ⃗ E C → Irr C and a boundary labelling of C is an assignment l: ⃗ ∂C → Irr C. We denote by L(C), L in (C) and L ∂ (C) respectively the sets of labellings, internal labellings, and boundary labellings of C. An (internal) labelling l of C is called a (internal) string-net labelling if l(e) = l(ē) for all e ∈ ⃗ E C. We denote by L SN (G) the set of all string-net labellings of C and by L in SN (C) the set of all internal string-net labellings of C. Proposition 4.",
    "4.44The map σ C | H C: H C → A(Σ C) is a unitary isomorphism.",
    "Moreover, for any connected boundary component S ∈ Bd(Σ C) of Σ C, we havea ▷ S σ C (ψ) = σ C t S (a)ψfor all ψ ∈ H C and all a ∈ Tube S. In particular, the skein subspace H C equipped with the Tube-actions given by the representations {t S } is a unitary A(∂Σ C)-module, and σ C | H C is an intertwiner of unitary A(∂Σ C)-modules.The proof appears in Appendix B.",
    "As a corollary, we obtain the commutativity lemma: Lemma 4.5."
  ]
}